Petalostigma pubescens

   [8473.jpg]
    Authority   Dom.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Dilleniidae:Euphorbiales:Euphorbiaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 8473

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A small tree usually 5-8 m but may reach up to 12 m
   in height. It often has a crooked trunk, dense canopy, and drooping
   branches. USES The wood can be used as fuel, and the bark and fruits
   have been used in the treatement of malaria, toothache, and sore eyes.
   GROWING PERIOD Relatively slow-growing perennial. COMMON NAMES Quinine
   tree, Quinine berry, Bitter bark, Native quince, Downy cracker bush.
   FURTHER INF Quinine tree occurs in northern and eastern Australia
   within the latitudinal range 11-30Â°S at elevations between sea level
   and 650 m. It can be found on sandstone plateaux, hilly uplands, and
   sandy, alluvial or stony plains. The foliage may be poisonous,
   perticularly after rain. (pH estimated by the compiler).

   Sources
   SOURCES (Petalostigma pubescens Dom.)
